      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are suffering from a condition known as \"lower stem chlorosis.\" This is often caused by a lack of iron in the soil, which is essential for the plants to produce chlorophyll, the green pigment that gives leaves their color. To fix this, you might want to consider adding some iron-rich fertilizer to the soil, or you could try using chelated iron supplements. Just be careful not to overdo it, as too much iron can also harm your plants. And remember, always check the soil pH, as it should be between 6.0 and 6.8 for optimal iron absorption. Keep an eye on your plants, and they'll thank you for your efforts. And don't forget, a little bit of care and attention can go a long way in keeping those pesky problems at bay. Happy gardening!",
